Let&#x27;s not judge Perl in general by the author&#x27;s Perl code, which starts with the baffling step of taking a reference to the argument array, then wraps it in a list and passes it to a function that immediately shifts it off the list and de-references it ….  Also, as Veedrac pointed out (<a href="https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=9562039" rel="nofollow">https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=9562039</a>), it carefully hashes the words by frequency, only to render the effort redundant by simply summing all the frequencies.  (Your Python does the same, I assume for fidelity to the original.)  A better Perl version might look like:<p><pre><code>    for my $file ( @ARGV ) {
        my $words;
        open my $fh, &#x27;<&#x27;, $file or die;
        local $/;
        say &quot;$file:  &quot;, scalar(split /\s+/, <$fh>), &quot; words&quot;;
    }
</code></pre>
EDIT:  Changed an explicit count of the `split` list into an implicit count via `scalar`.
